    <Vertical id="wpj2_Introduction">
       <Markdown>
            # Writing Process Journal 2
            ## Introduction
            
            One of the myths about writing is that people are either born good or bad writers,
            but research tells us that "writing requires practice for everyone, and all writers
            have more to learn" (Wardle and Downs 12). Yet if your teachers thought of writing
            like an innate talent rather than a learned skill, then you may have received feedback
            that reinforced the idea that you were born a good or bad writer. In fact, one of the
            threshold concepts _Writing About Writing_ introduces is, "writing is influenced by
            identities and prior experiences" (Wardle and Downs 12). Our experiences with writing
            start very early, and each time we encounter a new writing task, we come to that task
            with identities formed by all our prior experiences.            
            
            In this assignment, you'll reflect about the experiences that have shaped your
            understanding of what writing is, what makes someone a good writer, and how people
            learn to write well. 
            
            To complete this assignment, you will:
            
            - **Part 1**: Write about an experience that shaped your identity as a writer.
            - **Part 2**: Complete a survey that will help you reflect on your writing priorities.
            - **Part 3**: Define what you think good writing is, and explain how people can become better writers.
            - **Part 4**: Complete a self-evaluation form. What are your strengths and weaknesses as a writer?
       </Markdown>
    </Vertical>
    <Vertical id="wpj2_Step_1" title="What Makes a Good Writer?">
             <Markdown>
                 ## What Makes a Good Writer
                 
                 _Think about a moment, experience, or even a piece of feedback about writing
                 that made you feel like you were a good or bad writer. Tell us the story about
                 this experience. How did it shape the way you felt about yourself as a writer?
                 Do you think that people are naturally good or bad writers? Can everyone learn to write well?_
             </Markdown>
            <TextArea id="wpj2_define_good_writer" rows="12" placeholder="Enter your response here." />
    </Vertical>
    <Vertical id="wpj2_Step_2" title="Priorities for Successful Writing">
             <Markdown>
                 ## Priorities for Successful Writing
                 
                 In the screens that follow, you will explore which goals you think are important
                 for writing success. Each screen will present four goals that writer might adopt
                 at some point in the writing process. Decide which are more important and which
                 are less important, and indicate your decisions by dragging and dropping the
                 statements into priority order, where (1) is the highest priority and (4) is the lowest priority.
             </Markdown>
    </Vertical>
    <Vertical id="wpj2_Step_3" title="Sorting Priorities 1">
        <SimpleSortable id="wpj2_sortable1" title="What Do You Think Makes a Good Writer?">
            What do you think makes a good writer? Sort these writing skills from most important (top)
            to least important (bottom):
            ===
            1. Using sophisticated words and well-developed sentences.            
            2. Figuring out what one really thinks about a topic before writing.
            3. Taking the time to understand assignments before starting to write.            
            4. Expressing ideas accurately.
          </SimpleSortable>
